The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Aug. 17 (PTI): A government doctor who went on unauthorised leave for more than five years during a period of terrorist attacks in Punjab will lose five increments.          
	The Supreme Court has upheld the punishment on Dr P.L. Singla, after the high court and lower courts had quashed it.                  
	 The photograph with the story headlined Former governor lashes out on Page 4 in Sundays edition was that of S.K. Singh, the governor of Rajasthan, and not of S.K. Sinha, who resigned as Jammu and Kashmir governor in June, as mentioned in the caption. We apologise for the mistake.                  
	 Phagwara (PTI): Kuldip Ram alias Baba Manku, a monk at Punjabs Jamalpur village, has been arrested on rape charges, police said on Sunday. A woman of the village had complained that a drunken baba had followed her home from the shrine and raped her.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): Air India staff will not be allowed to go on foreign tours unless it is absolutely essential and would need permission from the chairman or the managing director, officials said. The airline has suffered losses of Rs 2,100 crore.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): A seller of talismans and charm rings, booked for foreign exchange violations 45 years ago, has got a clean chit from a Delhi court. The court rapped the enforcement directorate for its failure to examine witnesses and provide documents to prove the charge. Kuldip Singh Sud had been charged of attracting foreign customers through advertisements.                  
	 Puri (PTI): The chief priest of the Jagannath temple, Laxmi Narayan Patjoshi Mohapatra, died of cardiac arrest on Sunday. Mohapatra, 32, was ill for some time. His death has triggered uncertainty over a successor as his son is a minor and cant be appointed to the hereditary post.                                                                                                                         
